TY  - JOUR
T1  - Estimation of an Equilibrium Model With Externalities: Post-Disaster Neighborhood Rebuilding
AU  - Fu, Chao
AU  - Gregory, Jesse
Y1  - 2019/03/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14246
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 387
EP  - 421
VL  - 87
IS  - 2
KW  - Equilibrium models
KW  - externalities
KW  - structural estimation
KW  - regression discontinuity
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14246
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study the optimal design of subsidies in an equilibrium setting, where the decisions of individual recipients impose externalities on one another. We apply the model to the case of post-Katrina rebuilding in New Orleans under the Louisiana Road Home rebuilding grant program (RH). We estimate the structural model via indirect inference, exploiting a discontinuity in the formula for determining the size of grants, which helps isolate the causal effect of neighbors' rebuilding on one's own rebuilding choices. We find that the additional rebuilding induced by RH generated positive externalities equivalent to $4950 to each inframarginal household whose rebuilding choice was not affected by the program. Counterfactual policy experiments find that optimal subsidy policies bias grant offers against relocation, with an inverse-U-shaped relationship between the degree of bias and the severity of damages from the disaster.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Take the Short Route: Equilibrium Default and Debt Maturity
AU  - Aguiar, Mark
AU  - Amador, Manuel
AU  - Hopenhayn, Hugo
AU  - Werning, Iván
Y1  - 2019/03/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14806
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 423
EP  - 462
VL  - 87
IS  - 2
KW  - Sovereign debt
KW  - debt default
KW  - dilution
KW  - maturity choice
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14806
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We study the interactions between sovereign debt default and maturity choice in a setting with limited commitment for repayment as well as future debt issuances. Our main finding is that, under a wide range of conditions, the sovereign should, as long as default is not preferable, remain passive in long-term bond markets, making payments and retiring long-term bonds as they mature but never actively issuing or buying back such bonds. The only active debt-management margin is the short-term bond market. We show that any attempt to manipulate the existing maturity profile of outstanding long-term bonds generates losses, as bond prices move against the sovereign. Our results hold regardless of the shape of the yield curve. The yield curve captures the average costs of financing at different maturities but is misleading regarding the marginal costs.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Insurgency and Small Wars: Estimation of Unobserved Coalition Structures
AU  - Trebbi, Francesco
AU  - Weese, Eric
Y1  - 2019/03/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14436
T2  - Econometrica
